* **DevOps** (Development & Operations) is a set of practices and methods that **combine software development** (Dev) and **IT operations** (Ops) with the goal of **increasing the software lifecycle efficiency, speed and security** as well as **providing rapid and continuous delivery** of **high-quality software products** by **practicing agile methodology** **concepts**.  
* The core concept of DevOps is **the agile methodology** that emphasizes team **communication**, **collaboration** and **responsiveness to change** based on client-feedbacks as well as **continuous improvement** using an **iterative approach based on pre-planned sprints**.  
* The **IT operations** are related to infrastructure management:  
  * **System Administration**: Managing operating systems, installing updates and patches, ensuring system security, and optimizing performance.  
  * **Network Management**: Monitoring and managing the organization’s network, including routers, switches, firewalls, and load balancers, to ensure reliable and secure connectivity.  
  * **Monitoring and Performance Management**: Continuously monitoring systems and applications to detect issues, analyze performance, and ensure systems are running optimally in order to be ready to take decisions.  
  * … etc  
* DevOps **dimensions**:  
  * DevOps requires **cultural changes** because it requires **unifying teams**; it is not two separate teams (Dev team and Ops team) working in different silos; they both should be working in the same team while ensuring **collaboration** (sharing knowledge with individuals), **transparency** (be transparent with team when facing issues), **trust** (give freedom and independence to individuals) and **shared responsibility** (blameless culture).  
  * While **culture** is the foundation, **automation methods** (CI, CD, IaC …) and the right **tools** are **enablers** of the DevOps philosophy. **Automating repetitive tasks,** to speed up the PDLC and to avoid human errors (**Black Knight** catastrophe). These repetitive tasks include **integrating changes**, **testing**, **deploying**, and **monitoring**, which consequently frees up time for team members to focus on higher-value products.  
  * Testing is part of the CI and CD pipelines, it serves different role in each pipeline ;  
    * For CI: when new changes are detected the unit, integration, and end2end tests are executed to catch and fix bugs in the development stage.  
    * For CD: tests are used to ensure that the software is ready for deployment, it includes user acceptance (UAT), security and performance testing.  
* DevOps **practices** are mainly: *\[what actions and tasks do we do?\]*  
  * **Continuous Integration (CI)**: Continuous Integration involves developers frequently integrating their code changes into a shared repository (**to the development branch**) several times a day to avoid **merge conflicts** (working in **small batches** in Agile). Each integration is automatically **tested** (unit, integration, end to end) to detect integration errors early and integrated to the **main branch** after **peer reviews**.  
    * Tools: Git, Github, GitLab, Bitbucke, GitLab CI, Jenkin etc.  
  * **Continuous Delivery (CD):** Continuous Delivery **extends** CI by automatically **compiling** (eg. docker file), **signing**, **creating all necessary files** and **building** (bundles …) the software for **deployment without actually deploying**. Deploying all code changes to a testing or production environment after the build stage called **Continuous Deployment**. *This ensures that any integrated feature to the software main repository is released automatically to production*.  
  * **Infrastructure as code (IaC) :** IaC is the practice of **managing** and **configuring infrastructure through code,** rather than through **manual processes.** It involves using **scripts** and **configuration files** that contain **infrastructure specifications** (OS, patches, packages, Network configs …), which can be version-controlled.  
    * Tools: Docker, Kubernetes, Ansible, Chef, Puppet etc.  
  * **Automation (eg. Automated testing** and **Automated deployment):** Automated testing involves the use of scripts and tools to automatically test the software code. This includes unit tests, integration tests, functional tests, acceptance tests and more.  
    * Tools: Cucumber, Selenium, JUnit, Jasmine etc.  
  * **Collaboration:** Collaboration tools facilitate communication and coordination among team members. These tools include chat platforms (e.g., Microsoft Teams), project management tools (e.g., Jira, GitScrum), and version control systems (e.g., GitHub, GitLab, Bitbucket).  
  * **Containerization**: Using containers (e.g., Docker) to package applications and their dependencies in a consistent environment.  
  * **Monitoring and Logging**: Tracking application performance and infrastructure health in real time.  
    * Tools: Grafana, Kibana etc.

* DevOps **methods** are mainly: *\[what are the philosophies behind it?\]*  
  * **Agile methodology (Scrum, XP, Kanban** and **Lean):**  
    * customer-centric approach that mainly focuses on customer feedback in order to ensure continuous improvement of the product.  
    * Emphasizes team collaboration, communication and transparency.  
    * Requires efficient responsiveness to the changing requirements.  
    * Focuses on building the complete project by creating and integrating smaller blocks in an iterative approach.  
    * Values members and their interaction over tools and classic procedures.  
* DevOps **characteristics** are mainly: \[*what makes it different?\]*  
  * **Collaboration**  
  * **Automation**   
  * **Agility**  
  * **Rapid and Continuous improvement**  
  * **Secure and Resilient integration**  
  * **No humain failures**  
* Prior to the appearance of DevOps and Agile we used to work with the **waterfall methodology** that is a **unidirectional** and **sequential** (can’t jump to the next phase unless the current one is completed) **approach of managing the software life cycle**. The cons of this approach is that there is **no collaboration between the different teams** which leads to **conflicts and accumulation of errors, while going from one phase to another.** These errors could be **detected in a late stage of the PDLC** which  makes **going back up to the previous steps so expensive in terms of resources** (could be working on other projects or already changed company) **and time**.

![][image3]  
Fig.3: Waterfall methodology

* Agile is classified as an **iterative and client feedback-oriented approach** that is characterized by **efficient communication** and **collaboration** between teams as well as **flexible adaptation** to **variable needs**.  
* The agile approach is completely different from the Waterfall approach in that it **values individuals and interactions between them over tools and processes**. The main aim of agile methodology is to **emphasize communication and collaboration** between team members, as well as the **use of an iterative approach for continuous improvement** and **flexible adaptation** as required. In contrast, the Waterfall method is a **unidirectional approach** that l**acks effective communication and collaboration**, resulting in **high costs for modifications** or **going back to the previous stage**.  
  * No adaptation to changes;  
  * No immediate delivery;  
  * Accumulation of errors;  
  * Solving issues is expensive;

* **XP** and **Two Speed IT architecture** has contributed to the practices of DevOps.  
* **Extreme programming** is an Agile methodology that **focuses on development and testing**. ***It emphasizes having a high quality code for the delivered product*** by working in ***shorter and shorter feedback phases***. Its core keys are:  
  * **Embrace Change**: XP is designed to accommodate changing requirements even late in the development process.  
  * **Short Iterations**: Work is done in short, time-boxed iterations (typically 1-2 weeks), allowing for frequent feedback and adjustments.  
  * **Continuous Integration**: Developers integrate code changes frequently, often multiple times a day, to detect issues early.  
  * **Test-Driven Development (TDD)**: Tests are written before the code itself, ensuring that code is always tested and meets the required specifications.  
  * **Pair Programming**: Two developers, called **driver (junior eng.)** and **navigator (senior eng.)**, work together on the same code at one workstation, promoting knowledge sharing and code quality. The driver and navigator can switch roles after a predefined amount of time (e.g 20 mins).  
  * **Collective Code Ownership**: Any developer can improve any part of the codebase at any time, encouraging team responsibility for the entire project.  
  * **Simple Design**: Focus on designing only what is necessary for the current iteration to avoid over-engineering.  
  * **Refactoring**: Continuous improvement of the codebase by restructuring existing code without changing its external behavior, improving its readability and maintainability.  
  * **Sustainable Pace**: Teams work at a pace that can be sustained indefinitely, avoiding burnout and ensuring long-term productivity.  
  * **Coding Standards**: The team adheres to a consistent set of coding standards, making the codebase understandable and maintainable by all team members.
